---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import SiteHeader from "../components/SiteHeader.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Linkar | Reusable Analysis Resources For Humans And Machines"
  description="Linkar helps teams turn scripts, CLI tools, notebooks, and analysis steps into reusable templates and bindings, with a short CLI for humans and a local API for machines."
>
  <div class="page-shell">
    <SiteHeader />

    <main>
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-heading">
          <p class="eyebrow">What Linkar Is</p>
          <h2>A small runtime for reusable analysis work.</h2>
          <p class="section-copy">
            Data scientists often start from something useful already: a script, a package, a CLI
            tool, or a notebook. Then reality arrives. Inputs differ, defaults change, one step
            must feed another, and the same local adjustments get repeated by hand. That is where
            reuse becomes fragile and chaining becomes error-prone.
          </p>
          <p class="section-copy">
            The name reflects that goal: Linkar stands for <code>LINKing All Resources</code>.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="card-grid three-up">
          <article class="feature-card">
            <h3>Templates</h3>
            <p>
              Standalone units with explicit inputs, outputs, scripts, helpers, and tests.
            </p>
          </article>
          <article class="feature-card">
            <h3>Bindings</h3>
            <p>
              Reusable connection logic that links outputs to inputs and captures custom resolution once.
            </p>
          </article>
          <article class="feature-card">
            <h3>Projects</h3>
            <p>
              Readable local working state with recorded runs, stable paths, and inspectable metadata.
            </p>
          </article>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="section section-alt">
        <div class="section-heading">
          <p class="eyebrow">Interfaces</p>
          <h2>One runtime, two entry points.</h2>
          <p class="section-copy">
            Humans use the CLI. Machines use the local API or MCP. Both paths write the same run
            artifact on disk.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="interface-grid">
          <article class="interface-card">
            <div class="interface-head">
              <span class="interface-tag">Human</span>
              <h3>Short CLI</h3>
            </div>
            <p>
              Discover the current project, expose template params as flags, and keep the common
              path short.
            </p>
            <pre><code>linkar config author set --name "Your Name"
linkar project init --name study
cd study
linkar pack add ../examples/packs/chaining --id chaining --binding default
linkar run produce_message --message "hello"
linkar run consume_message
linkar inspect run consume_message_001</code></pre>
          </article>

          <article class="interface-card">
            <div class="interface-head">
              <span class="interface-tag">Machine</span>
              <h3>Structured API</h3>
            </div>
            <p>
              Inspect templates, resolve params, run work, and read outputs without shell scraping.
            </p>
            <pre><code>linkar serve --port 8000 --api-token local-dev:read,resolve,execute

GET  /v1
GET  /v1/schema
POST /v1/templates/&lcub;template_id&rcub;:resolve
POST /v1/templates/&lcub;template_id&rcub;:run
GET  /v1/projects/current/runs/latest?run_ref=methods
POST /v1/runs:collect
GET  /v1/runs/&lcub;run_ref&rcub;/outputs
GET  /v1/runs/&lcub;run_ref&rcub;/status

linkar mcp serve</code></pre>
          </article>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-heading">
          <p class="eyebrow">Read In Order</p>
          <h2>Concepts, tutorials, then examples.</h2>
          <p class="section-copy">
            Keep the path simple. Read the concepts first, use the tutorials to do real work, and
            use the bundled examples when you want the smallest runnable pack for a specific case.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="card-grid three-up">
          <a class="doc-card" href={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}explanations/`}>
            <h3>Concepts</h3>
            <p>Understand templates, bindings, packs, and projects.</p>
          </a>
          <a class="tutorial-card tutorial-link" href={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}tutorials/`}>
            <h3>Tutorials</h3>
            <p>Start a project, build a pack, and use Linkar step by step.</p>
          </a>
          <a class="doc-card" href={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}examples/`}>
            <h3>Examples</h3>
            <p>Jump into bundled packs for authoring, bindings, pack selection, and remote use.</p>
          </a>
        </div>

        <div class="hero-actions section-top-gap">
          <a class="button button-primary" href={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}tutorials/getting-started/`}>Start with getting started</a>
        </div>
      </section>
    </main>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
